"codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Reward accounting mixes raw deposits and LP shares, enabling reward theft and withdrawal lockups","locations":["0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:145","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:168","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:203","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:252","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:292","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:296"],"claim":"`provideLiquidity()` and `withdrawLiquidity()` accrue rewards using `mm.tokenAmount + mm.ethAmount`, while `claimReward()` computes the user's accumulated rewards using `mm.lpShares`. Once LP shares diverge from raw deposited balances, especially after orderbook outflows shrink `pool.totalLiquidity`, reward accounting becomes inconsistent.","impact":"Attackers can claim rewards accrued before they joined by first obtaining inflated LP shares and then calling `claimReward()`. In the opposite direction, once `rewardDebt` is reset from the larger `lpShares` basis, later reward updates or withdrawals can underflow and revert, locking an LP's rewards or exit path until pool state changes.","paths":["Rewards accrue so `pool.accRewardPerShare` becomes non-zero.","Orderbook outflows reduce `pool.totalLiquidity`, letting a new depositor mint more `lpShares` than their recorded `tokenAmount + ethAmount` would justify.","The depositor calls `claimReward()`, which uses `mm.lpShares * accRewardPerShare` and therefore overpays them relative to their recorded contribution.","After `claimReward()` stores a `rewardDebt` based on LP shares, a later `withdrawLiquidity()` or additional liquidity update may compute pending rewards from the smaller raw-deposit basis and revert on underflow."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Nominal token amounts are credited even when fewer tokens are actually received","locations":["0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:138","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:165","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:174","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:535","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:538"],"claim":"Both `provideLiquidity()` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook()` trust the requested token amount after `safeTransferFrom` instead of measuring the contract's balance delta. For fee-on-transfer or otherwise short-transferring tokens, pool and user accounting are increased by more tokens than the contract actually received.","impact":"The pool can become undercollateralized and later withdrawals or orderbook transfers can revert because `pool.totalToken` exceeds the real token balance. If enough honest liquidity later enters the system, the undercredited depositor can also withdraw more value than they truly contributed.","paths":["A supported token transfers less than the requested amount because of transfer fees or other non-standard behavior.","A user calls `provideLiquidity()` with `tokenAmount = 100`, but the contract actually receives only 90 tokens.","The contract still credits `mm.tokenAmount += 100`, `pool.totalToken += 100`, and mints shares from the inflated accounting.","Later withdrawals and pool transfers are calculated from the overstated totals, causing insolvency or value extraction from later liquidity."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"A full orderbook drain bricks the pool because returned assets are rejected when liquidity reaches zero","locations":["0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:159","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:197","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:435","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:439","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:467","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:472","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:501","0x37ea5f691bce8459c66ffceeb9cf34ffa32fdadc/contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:532"],"claim":"The orderbook can legally transfer out all remaining pool assets until `pool.totalLiquidity` becomes zero, but both `receiveETHFromOrderbook()` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook()` require `pool.totalLiquidity > 0`. Once a pool is fully drained, returned assets are rejected, `withdrawLiquidity()` also rejects exits, and new deposits revert because share minting divides by `pool.totalLiquidity` while `pool.totalLPShares` is still non-zero.","impact":"A normal or malicious full orderbook drain can permanently lock all LP capital and any inventory sitting in the orderbook. The pool becomes unrecoverable on-chain because assets cannot be returned and LPs cannot withdraw or meaningfully recapitalize it.","paths":["A pool has non-zero ETH and token balances with outstanding LP shares.","The orderbook transfers out all token inventory and all ETH inventory across one or more calls, reducing `pool.totalLiquidity` to zero while `pool.totalLPShares` remains positive.","When the orderbook later tries to return either asset, `receiveETHFromOrderbook()` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook()` revert on `require(pool.totalLiquidity > 0, \"No liquidity\")`.","LPs are then stuck: `withdrawLiquidity()` rejects because the pool has no liquidity, and new deposits revert because minting uses `pool.totalLPShares / pool.totalLiquidity`."],"round":1,"source_agents":["merge-review"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Owner can unconditionally drain all pool and reward assets","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"This is an explicit `onlyOwner` emergency escape hatch documented in the contract comments. Without evidence that privileged emergency powers are out of scope or hidden from users, this is a trust-model/centralization concern rather than a distinct code vulnerability."},{"title":"The `minTokenAmount` parameter provides no real slippage protection","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`minTokenAmount` is redundant, but the function still enforces the live reserve ratio within a hard ±1% band. The issue does not create a concrete exploit or meaningful additional user harm beyond a misleading parameter name."}]}
