/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/aave_boost_1777215065/rounds/round_3/merge_stderr.log:31:    "id": "F-001",
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/aave_boost_1777215065/rounds/round_3/merge_stderr.log:307:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Verifier has no withdrawal path, permanently locking the prefunded bankroll and any recovered assets","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:86","FlawVerifier.sol:160","FlawVerifier.sol:163"],"claim":"`FlawVerifier` is designed to be prefunded with a very large native-token balance and can accumulate additional ETH and ERC20 balances during `executeOnOpportunity()`, but the contract exposes no owner-controlled withdrawal, sweep, or destruction path to return those assets to an operator.","impact":"All prefunded native tokens, any profit realized by the strategy, and any residual ERC20 balances can become permanently inaccessible inside the contract, resulting in total loss of control over the verifier treasury.","paths":["Fund `FlawVerifier` with native tokens before execution","Call `executeOnOpportunity()`; the contract receives/retains ETH and AAVE","No function exists to transfer native tokens or ERC20 balances back to an operator"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Anyone can trigger the strategy against the verifier treasury","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:86"],"claim":"`executeOnOpportunity()` is `external` and completely permissionless even though it controls a prefunded treasury and decides when the contract will spend its own assets against external protocols.","impact":"Any third party can front-run the intended operator and consume or spoil a time-sensitive opportunity, forcing execution at an unfavorable moment and potentially leaving the bankroll and any resulting profit stranded in the contract earlier than intended.","paths":["Observe the verifier being funded","Call `executeOnOpportunity()` before the intended operator does","The contract executes the strategy using its own treasury with no caller authorization"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Zero-minimum-output swaps let MEV searchers siphon away most of the extracted value","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:136","FlawVerifier.sol:152"],"claim":"Both Uniswap V2 swap calls use `amountOutMin = 0`, so the verifier accepts any execution price for both the seed ETH-to-AAVE buy and the final AAVE-to-ETH liquidation.","impact":"A searcher can sandwich the transaction, push the AAVE/WETH price sharply against the verifier for each leg, and capture most of the exploitable value while still allowing the transaction to satisfy the minimal profit check.","paths":["Observe `executeOnOpportunity()` in the public mempool","Front-run to worsen the AAVE/WETH price before one or both swaps","Let the verifier swap with `amountOutMin = 0` at the manipulated price","Back-run to restore price and keep the spread"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Verifier accepts target-controlled token and pool addresses without validation","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:89","FlawVerifier.sol:90","FlawVerifier.sol:91","FlawVerifier.sol:111","FlawVerifier.sol:125","FlawVerifier.sol:147"],"claim":"`executeOnOpportunity()` reads `aave()` and `pool()` from `TARGET` at runtime and then treats those addresses as trusted for balance checks, the 1 ETH bootstrap swap, approvals, and `withdraw()`. The verifier never pins them to known-good contracts or validates that they are the intended AAVE token and pool.","impact":"If `TARGET` is misconfigured, upgraded, or adversarial, it can redirect the verifier into buying a bogus token with treasury ETH, approving the wrong asset, or calling an attacker-controlled pool during withdrawal. That can burn bankroll, strand the strategy, or hand execution to malicious external code.","paths":["A malicious or misconfigured `TARGET` returns an unexpected token from `aave()` and/or an attacker-controlled contract from `pool()`","`_prepareNonZeroAaveInput()` spends 1 ETH on the returned token and approves it for `TARGET`","The verifier later calls `withdraw()` on the returned pool address and cannot distinguish the fake dependency from the intended one"],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"One-second AMM deadlines make the strategy trivially censorable","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:141","FlawVerifier.sol:154"],"claim":"Both swaps use `block.timestamp + 1` as the deadline, leaving almost no inclusion slack and making successful execution depend on near-immediate block inclusion.","impact":"Normal congestion or deliberate builder/validator delay can cause the swaps to expire and revert, creating an easy denial-of-service condition for a time-sensitive execution path.","paths":["Broadcast `executeOnOpportunity()`","The transaction lands more than one second after submission","One of the swaps reverts because the deadline has expired"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Unlimited AAVE approval to TARGET can expose all verifier inventory","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:111","FlawVerifier.sol:156"],"claim":"When the zero-input deposit path fails, `_prepareNonZeroAaveInput()` grants `TARGET` a max allowance over the verifier's AAVE and never revokes or scopes it to the intended single-unit deposit amount.","impact":"If `TARGET` can ever invoke `transferFrom()` itself, or expose any path that does so, it can sweep not just the 1-unit seed profit check","If the aggregate gas use is too high, the transaction runs out of gas or becomes economically non-viable, preventing recovery"],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"A single wei of DAI can brick every future recovery attempt","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:57","FlawVerifier.sol:96","FlawVerifier.sol:103"],"claim":"`executeOnOpportunity()` unconditionally tries to liquidate any positive DAI balance. Because Uniswap V2 rounds sufficiently tiny swaps down to zero output, an attacker can transfer 1 wei of DAI to the contract and force `_swapTokenToEth(DAI)` to revert when the router attempts to swap that balance, causing the entire `executeOnOpportunity()` transaction to revert on every run until additional DAI is donated.","impact":"Any external account can cheaply and permissionlessly deny service to the recovery flow, blocking liquidation of legitimately recovered WBTC/USDC/USDT/WETH proceeds as well. Since the contract has no token rescue or dust-clearing path, the griefing balance can persist indefinitely and strand future recoveries.","paths":["An attacker transfers 1 wei of DAI to `FlawVerifier`","A caller invokes `executeOnOpportunity()`","`_swapTokenToEth(DAI)` observes `bal > 0` and calls the Uniswap V2 router with `amountIn = 1`","The swap computes zero ETH output for that tiny amount and reverts, bubbling the failure up","The whole transaction reverts, so no bounty sweep or liquidation can complete until more DAI is added"],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Profit check can be satisfied with preloaded token balances instead of new recovery profit","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:50","FlawVerifier.sol:54","FlawVerifier.sol:58","FlawVerifier.sol:63","FlawVerifier.sol:96"],"claim":"`executeOnOpportunity()` snapshots only the contract's native ETH balance as `initialBalance`, then counts any pre-existing WETH or supported ERC20s already sitting in the contract after they are unwrapped or swapped during the same call. A caller can therefore donate roughly `0.1 ether` worth of WETH, or enough swappable WBTC/USDC/USDT/DAI, before invoking `executeOnOpportunity()` and make the final `Insufficient profit` check pass even if `_sweepBounties()` recovered nothing.","impact":"This defeats the verifier's only profitability gate. A third party can use their own tokens to force otherwise unprofitable sweep attempts, causing the contract to run the full external `startPool`/`endPool` mutation sequence at arbitrary times even when no new value was recovered. If the underlying opportunity is timing-sensitive or one-shot, that can consume it or leave later legitimate recovery attempts with nothing to claim.","paths":["Transfer at least `0.1 ether` worth of WETH, or enough supported swappable tokens, to `FlawVerifier`","Call `executeOnOpportunity()`","The function measures `initialBalance` using only native ETH, then unwraps or swaps the donated token inventory into ETH","The final `require(address(this).balance >= initialBalance + 0.1 ether)` passes even if `_sweepBounties()` produced no new proceeds"],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-009","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"USDC or USDT blacklisting can permanently DoS all future recoveries","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:55","FlawVerifier.sol:56","FlawVerifier.sol:96","FlawVerifier.sol:103"],"claim":"The contract must successfully swap any positive USDC or USDT balance through Uniswap, but it has no skip path, rescue path, or per-token isolation if those centralized stablecoins refuse transfers. If this contract is ever blacklisted or transfer-blocked by USDC or USDT while holding a positive balance, `_swapTokenToEth()` reverts and aborts the entire `executeOnOpportunity()` transaction.","impact":"A single blocked USDC or USDT balance prevents liquidation of every other recovered asset as well, because the whole recovery transaction reverts before completion. Since the contract has no token rescue mechanism, subsequent bounty proceeds can remain stranded behind one centralized-token failure mode indefinitely.","paths":["`_sweepBounties()` or a direct transfer leaves a positive USDC or USDT balance in `FlawVerifier`","The token issuer blacklists this contract or otherwise causes transfers from it to fail","A later `executeOnOpportunity()` call reaches `_swapTokenToEth(USDC)` or `_swapTokenToEth(USDT)`","The router transfer fails and the full recovery transaction reverts, blocking liquidation of all assets"],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Anyone can trigger the one-shot bounty sweep and consume opportunities at arbitrary times","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`executeOnOpportunity()` is permissionless, but permissionless execution alone is not a reportable flaw from this code. The claimed harm depends on unproven assumptions about privileged operator intent or one-shot target-side semantics; the concrete guard-bypass angle is captured separately in F-007."},{"title":"`endPool` is attempted even when `startPool` failed, expanding the attack surface to pre-existing pools","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"The code does unconditionally call `endPool`, but reportable harm depends entirely on undocumented `SILICA.endPool` behavior for pre-existing pools. Without evidence that `endPool` can damage unrelated pools in this situation, the candidate remains too speculative."}]}
