/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/rubic_t01_clean/rounds/round_1/merge_stderr.log:466:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"`routerCallNative` can be abused as an arbitrary approved-token spender to drain users with live proxy allowances","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:99","FlawVerifier.sol:180","FlawVerifier.sol:203","FlawVerifier.sol:223","FlawVerifier.sol:308","Contract.sol.disabled_exp_poc:88","Contract.sol.disabled_exp_poc:116","Contract.sol.disabled_exp_poc:118","Contract.sol.disabled_exp_poc:127","Contract.sol.disabled_exp_poc:129"],"claim":"The in-scope exploit harnesses consistently show that Rubic proxy `routerCallNative` entrypoints accept attacker-controlled `router` and raw calldata even when all swap fields are zeroed. By setting `router` to the USDC token contract and `_data` to `transferFrom(victim, attacker, amount)`, the proxy itself acts as the spender and can pull funds from any account that previously approved that proxy. The PoCs rank victims by `min(balance, allowance)` and then invoke the proxy to execute the token pull, which is strong evidence that the underlying proxy path lacks validation that `router` is safe and that the calldata corresponds to a legitimate bridge/swap flow.","impact":"Any user with a lingering ERC20 allowance to the affected Rubic proxy can be permissionlessly drained for up to their approved balance. This is direct theft of user funds and can be repeated across many victims in a single transaction, causing protocol-wide loss.","paths":["Victim grants or leaves an ERC20 allowance to a Rubic proxy.","Attacker crafts `BaseCrossChainParams` with `srcInputToken = address(0)`, `srcInputAmount = 0`, and `router = address(USDC)`.","Attacker encodes `_data` as `transferFrom(victim, attacker, amount)` where `amount = min(victimBalance, victimAllowanceToProxy)`.","Attacker calls the relevant `routerCallNative` entrypoint on the proxy.","Because the proxy performs the external call as the already-approved spender, the victim's tokens are transferred to the attacker and can then be liquidated."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Transfer helper libraries silently accept EOAs or non-contract token addresses as successful transfers","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"The libraries in `interface.sol` are generic vendored helpers, and there is no in-scope callsite showing protocol accounting that trusts these helpers with a user-controlled or misconfigured token address. Without a concrete reachable integration, this is too speculative."},{"title":"Unsafe approve wrappers preserve the classic ERC20 allowance race","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"This is a well-known ERC20 caveat rather than a protocol-specific bug here. The only visible approval flow in scope (`FlawVerifier._approveIfNeeded`) resets to zero before setting a new allowance, so the candidate is not supported by an in-scope vulnerable usage."},{"title":"ETH transfer helpers forward all gas and can reenter integrating contracts","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Forwarding gas is not itself a reportable issue; it becomes one only with a concrete caller that updates critical state after the send. No such in-scope usage is present."},{"title":"Unsafe fixed-point division helpers return zero on divide-by-zero instead of reverting","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"These helpers are explicitly named `unsafe*` and no sensitive in-scope pricing, accounting, or solvency logic reuses them. Absent a concrete vulnerable callsite, this is only a theoretical misuse warning."},{"title":"Minimal proxy library does not verify that the implementation has deployed code","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`Clones` is a generic library and there is no in-scope factory or deployment path using attacker- or admin-supplied implementations. The candidate lacks a supported exploit path in this codebase."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/0xf340_find_validate_p8/rounds/round_1/agent_codex/stdout.log:3:    "id": "F-001",
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/thenftv2_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Per-token approvals are not cleared on owner or operator transfers, allowing stale approved addresses to steal NFTs","locations":["0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:311","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:337","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:354","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:443"],"claim":"`approval[tokenId]` is only cleared in the branch where the approved address itself calls `transferFrom`/`safeTransferFrom`. When the owner or an `approvalAll` operator moves the NFT, `_transfer` updates balances and ownership but never resets the old single-token approval. That stale approved address remains authorized against the new owner and can later call `transferFrom` to seize the token. The same stale approval also survives a burn because `burn()` calls `_transfer` directly.","impact":"A previously approved address can steal NFTs after they are sold or otherwise transferred by the owner/operator. It can also reclaim a burned NFT from `DEAD_ADDRESS` without paying the 5 DAO restore cost, bypassing the intended restoration payment flow.","paths":["Owner approves attacker for token `id` via `approve(attacker, id)` -> owner or operator transfers token to a buyer via `transferFrom` or `safeTransferFrom` -> approval is not cleared -> attacker calls `transferFrom(buyer, attacker, id)` and succeeds.","Owner approves attacker for token `id` -> owner calls `burn(id)` -> token moves to `DEAD_ADDRESS` but approval persists -> attacker calls `transferFrom(DEAD_ADDRESS, attacker, id)` and restores the NFT without paying DAO fees."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"ERC165 advertises enumerable and receiver interfaces that the contract does not actually honor","locations":["0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:232","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:241","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:253","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:428","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:451"],"claim":"`supportsInterface()` returns true for `IERC721Enumerable` and `IERC721TokenReceiver`, but the implementation does not satisfy either interface's expected behavior. `totalSupply()` returns `max` rather than the number of assigned tokens, `tokenOfOwnerByIndex()` ignores `_owner` and simply returns `_index` if any token is assigned there, and `onERC721Received()` always reverts instead of accepting transfers and returning the selector.","impact":"Integrators that trust ERC165 can mis-enumerate ownership, miscount supply, or attempt safe transfers into this contract and hit unexpected reverts. That can break marketplace indexing, custody flows, and other integrations built around standard ERC721 behavior.","paths":["Integrator checks `supportsInterface(type(IERC721Enumerable).interfaceId)` -> uses `totalSupply`/`tokenOfOwnerByIndex` to enumerate holdings -> receives token IDs unrelated to the queried owner or unminted IDs -> downstream accounting or UI logic misbehaves.","External contract or bridge checks `supportsInterface(type(IERC721TokenReceiver).interfaceId)` -> attempts `safeTransferFrom` into this contract -> `onERC721Received()` reverts and the transfer path fails unexpectedly."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Approval events log the caller instead of the actual token owner","locations":["0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:320","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:346","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:363","0x79a7d3559d73ea032120a69e59223d4375deb595/Contract.sol:383"],"claim":"The contract emits `Approval(msg.sender, ...)` instead of `Approval(owner, ...)`. When an operator approves a spender, or when an approved spender clears approval during transfer, the log's indexed owner field does not match the token's true owner.","impact":"Off-chain systems that reconstruct approval state from logs can desynchronize from on-chain reality, causing incorrect approval displays, stale listings, or misattributed authorization history.","paths":["Owner grants `setApprovalForAll(operator, true)` -> operator calls `approve(spender, tokenId)` -> emitted `Approval` event records `operator` as owner even though `ownerOf(tokenId)` is unchanged.","Approved spender transfers the token -> contract emits approval-clear event with the spender in the owner field -> log-based indexers can mis-handle approval invalidation."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Incomplete require statement causes compilation failure","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. `require(_holder != address(0));` is valid Solidity syntax and compiles normally."},{"title":"Unchecked return values in restore function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. Both ERC20 `transferFrom` calls in `restore()` are wrapped in `require`, so restoration cannot proceed if either payment fails."},{"title":"Missing token existence validation in burn function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. `burn()` uses a mapping, not an array; out-of-range IDs do not read garbage. For unset IDs `ownership[id]` is `address(0)`, so the owner check fails for any real caller."},{"title":"Missing token existence validation in restore function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. Mapping reads for unset IDs return `address(0)`, so `require(DEAD_ADDRESS == ownership[id])` fails. There is no out-of-bounds read primitive here."},{"title":"Missing zero-address validation in constructor","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. This is deployer misconfiguration risk, not a permissionless protocol vulnerability."},{"title":"Incorrect event parameter ordering in Transfer event","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. `emit Transfer(_from, _to, _tokenId)` uses the correct ERC721 argument order, and the candidate's duplicate-event rationale is not a vulnerability."},{"title":"Curator role is not immutable and can be renounced","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. The current source has no `renounceOwnership()` path in the audited contract, and curator reassignment is an intentional privileged admin action rather than a security flaw."},{"title":"Missing SafeMath for arithmetic operations","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. The contract uses Solidity `^0.8.11`, which has built-in checked arithmetic."},{"title":"Token ID range not validated in approve function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. `approve()` already checks `_tokenId < max`, and non-minted tokens cannot be approved because the authorization check fails when `ownership[_tokenId]` is zero."},{"title":"Missing validation in tokenOfOwnerByIndex","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Merged into F-002. The function is indeed broken, but the reportable issue is the broader false `IERC721Enumerable` support claim and resulting integration breakage."},{"title":"onERC721Received reverts instead of returning selector","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Merged into F-002. Reverting is only reportable here because `supportsInterface()` advertises receiver support."},{"title":"Missing Return Values in ERC721 Interface Functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Rejected. The candidate misstates the code: `supportsInterface()` returns true for both `IERC721Enumerable` and `IERC721TokenReceiver`."}]}
